title: For Sale/Trade:  Scammers are out today, flag'em
postcontent:
The easiest way to pick out a scam is to highlight the text of the item description and cut and paste it into a google search. This will usually pull up a link to the site the ad was "borrowed" from.

Scammers usually register day of listing if they register at all. Typically they put up 3 items like AR's, all with different backgrounds in the pics. Usually if you google the name of the listing you will find it's a gunbroker auction. You can also search images in google as well. If you see the word auction in the listing it's probably cut and pasted from an auction site. If the seller has items listed in 3 different non contiguous states, probably a scam. Many legitimate sellers will put there location down as "state, state" such as "Oklahoma, Oklahoma" but scammers do this as well. All the adds with the "Jacksons Armory" business cards are pulled directly from Gunbroker. You will never get an FTF transaction with a scammer. If you see these adds, take a moment to flag them so they don't clutter up the board. It's an outstanding resource.

title: For Sale:  Firestorm .380  (With 1,100 rounds of Ammo)
postcontent:
$250 is for the gun only! $800 for the gun and ammo!! Bersa Firestorm .380 ACP. It comes with original box / paperwork, 2-magazines, 1,000 rounds of PMC FMJ 90 Gr, and 100 rounds of Silver Bear FMJ 92 gr. That is a total of 1,100 rounds of ammo. This is a very nice and well kept pistol. I am asking $800 Or Best Offer for the gun and ammo. I might be willing to sell the gun or ammo separate. Contact Chris at REDACTED

Bersa Firestorm .380 Review: Not top-of-the-line, but hard to pass up
3/12/12 | by Jim Downey   3 44
The Bersa Firestorm
Bersa is an Argentine firearms company that isn’t hugely known in the U.S., which is a bit of a shame because generally the Bersa handguns I have handled were quite nice and very good bargains. The Bersa Firestorm .380 ACP is no exception to this.

In this review I will also reference the Bersa Thunder as well as the Firestorm because the two are pretty much the same gun. The Firestorm model is actually assembled in the U.S. with Argentine parts, and, in the end, has only a couple of very minor differences. Since the Firestorm is the version I have shot more recently while testing its ballistics for BallisticsByTheInch.com, it is the basis for this review, but I think most everything I have to say would be applicable to the Thunder version as well.

Where it got its good looks
The Firestorm is a direct blowback, medium-sized .380 built on the Walther PPK design. A design, I might add, that has proven itself to be dependable time and time again for more than 80 years.

Overall the Firestorm is a well-made little gun and manufactured with quality materials. The frame is an aluminum alloy, which contributes to the lighter weight (just 20 ounces), but also proves to be strong and durable. The slide and other components are made from high quality steel. For costing, at most, $300, these guns are durable. There have been reports of Bersas lasting 50,000 rounds before having problems.

The gun features a fixed barrel (mounted to the frame) that helps give it stability and accuracy. The beavertail on the back of the grip is a little longer than on the original PPK design, which helps keep large hands from getting ‘bitten’ by the operation of the slide/hammer (something I very much appreciate). And there is a finger extension on the magazine that also allows for better control—a design tweak introduced on the PPK about 40 years ago.

Fit and finish for the Firestorm is likewise good. It’s not the same quality that you’ll see on high-end firearms, but it isn’t bad at all.

Trigger and Action
The Firestorm has an exposed hammer and de-cocker, which is, again, similar to the PPK. The long double-action pull on the trigger for the first shot is followed by a crisp shorter single-action pull for subsequent shots.

I’ve found the triggers on all the Bersa guns to be decent or better—the Firestorm I would describe as “good”, but without the roughness you might find typical of lesser-priced firearms.

Differences between Firestorm and Thunder
The Firestorm has a front-dot sight and a rear notched sight, which is outlined in white. This is one of the minor differences between the Firestorm and the Thunder versions: the Thunder has a three-dot sight.

Another minor difference is that the Firestorm comes with a rubber wrap-around grip with finger indents, whereas the Thunder has traditional side panel grips with a grooved backstrap and smooth front.

Final Thoughts
A lot of people consider the Firestorm/Thunder to be a “pocket pistol.” I tend not to. With the finger grip extension and 20-ounce weight, I think they are a little too big for that use.

In this day and age with a variety of ‘micro .380s’, there are probably better choices for use as a pocket gun. But that is not to say that the Firestorm or Thunder is too large for concealed-carry duty. Hardly. It would disappear into a belt holster or into a shoulder rig (the way the PPK it was modeled on did for James Bond). And personally, I like the slightly larger size and weight to control recoil and increase accuracy. I consider this gun to be a very good choice for self-defense use. Yes, even though it is chambered for the .380 ACP, which is adequate with the correct ammunition.

Bottom line, if you get a chance, take a look at the Bersa guns, particularly the Firestorm or Thunder. They are well made, the company stands behind their product (for life for the original owner) and while the fit and finish may not be top-of-the-line, neither is the price. It is a very good value firearm.

title: For Trade:  Walther PPK 380
postcontent:
I have a PPK in excellent condition. Like to trade to a Sig but open to other offers

I've gotten several questions about the German markings on the slide: 

The gun is a .380 but is marked 9mm kurz on the slide because kurz is German for "short." 9mm kurz, or short, and .380 rounds are the same thing, just different names. So basically it is for the German and American reference. Which also explains why in Bond movies they refer to his guns as 9mm, when in reality Bond is carrying the .380 PPK as offered here.

title: For Sale:  Taurus 607 .357 Magnum 7-shot 6.5" Revolver
location: Woods Cross, Salt Lake City, Utah
postcontent:
Just dropped price down from $450!  

This is a beast of a revolver that feels like it ought to be taking zombie heads off.  The gun is in mint condition for a gun made in 1996, and the glossy blueing is almost perfect.  No scratches, and only tiny wear spots on some corners.  It sports a 6.5″ long ribbed and ported barrel with adjustable rear sight, and holds 7 rounds.  I tried a few heavy .357 loads through it, and the weight and balance of the gun make them extremely controlled shots.  The action is very smooth, with a crisp single action pull.  Practice with .38 specials and you hardly know you’re shooting anything.  The gun is accurate as well as beautiful.

To complete the package, I’m including a custom made leather drop-leg holster with adjustable thigh strap and buckle.  It puts this heavy piece in a comfortable draw-level position, and looks completely bad walking around camp.  Nice to wear while riding an ATV to have it right there on your leg.

I don’t know the whole history of this gun, but I have only put a few rounds through it to see how it shoots.  The guy who sold it to me said it basically sat for 10 years.  I went over it in detail.  Tight lockup, very clean–It looks like a gun only a couple of years old.

I’m including with it the original black rubber grips that were on it, but I just added a set of $75 hardwood grips with finger grooves that feel and look awesome.  This pistol honestly shoots almost as well as my Smith and Wesson .357.  Since I have both, I don't use this one much.  It’s tempting to keep it, but I’m looking for a smaller revolver right now.  I might trade for something like a J-frame Smith and Wesson or Ruger SP101 with 3″ or 4″ barrel.

Please text or email me with questions, or if you want more photos.  You can check this other site that has a few more pictures: http://utahguns.com/category/307/Handguns/listings/28789/Taurus-607-357-7-shot-65-Revolver.html.  Now that I've dropped the price, I'm pretty firm on price, but it comes with several extras.  I'll even give you a box of .38 practice reloads to get you started if you want.  This is a sweet gun and needs a home!
